---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'Top Tax Deductions for Freelancers & 1099 Workers (2025–2026)';
const description =
  'The tax deductions that matter most for freelancers and 1099 workers — home office, mileage, health insurance, retirement, and the 20% QBI deduction — and which ones lower both self-employment tax and income tax versus income tax only.';

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Which deductions lower both self-employment tax and income tax?',
    a: 'Ordinary business expenses claimed on Schedule C — home office, mileage, phone and internet, supplies, software, and education — all reduce your net profit. Because both self-employment tax and income tax are calculated from that net profit, every dollar of a legitimate Schedule C expense lowers both taxes at once.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Which deductions only lower income tax?',
    a: 'Above-the-line and personal deductions taken after net profit is set only reduce income tax. That includes the deduction for half of your self-employment tax, self-employed health insurance premiums, SEP-IRA and Solo 401(k) contributions, and the 20% Qualified Business Income (QBI) deduction. They do not shrink the self-employment tax you owe.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I deduct my home office if I rent?',
    a: 'Yes. Renters and homeowners can both claim the home office deduction as long as part of the home is used regularly and exclusively for business. You can use the simplified method or the actual-expense method — whichever gives the larger, well-documented deduction.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How does the 20% QBI deduction work?',
    a: 'The Qualified Business Income deduction can remove up to 20% of your qualified business profit from taxable income, lowering only your income tax. It has income thresholds and limits based on your business type, so the full 20% is not guaranteed for every freelancer.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Do I need receipts to claim these deductions?',
    a: 'Yes. Keep records for every deduction — receipts, invoices, a mileage log, and bank or card statements. If the IRS ever asks, you must be able to show the expense was ordinary, necessary, and business-related. Good records also make your annual return far easier to prepare.',
  },
];

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })),
};

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Top Tax Deductions for Freelancers & 1099 Workers',
  description,
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: '1099 Estimator' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: '1099 Estimator', url: 'https://1099estimator.com' },
  mainEntityOfPage: 'https://1099estimator.com/guides/self-employed-tax-deductions',
};

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://1099estimator.com' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Guides', item: 'https://1099estimator.com/guides' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'Tax Deductions', item: 'https://1099estimator.com/guides/self-employed-tax-deductions' },
  ],
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} schema={[articleSchema, faqSchema, breadcrumbSchema]}>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-12">
    <!-- Breadcrumb -->
    <nav class="text-sm text-slate-400" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-indigo-700">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-1.5">/</span>
      <a href="/guides" class="hover:text-indigo-700">Guides</a>
      <span class="mx-1.5">/</span>
      <span class="text-slate-600">Tax deductions</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="mt-6">
      <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-xs font-semibold text-indigo-700 bg-indigo-100/80 ring-1 ring-indigo-200 rounded-full px-3 py-1">
        <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500"></span> Updated for the 2025 &amp; 2026 tax years
      </span>
      <h1 class="mt-5 text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 text-balance">
        Top tax deductions for freelancers &amp; 1099 workers
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">
        Deductions are the single biggest lever a self-employed person has to lower their tax bill. But not all
        deductions are equal — some cut both of your taxes, and some cut only one. Here is how to tell them apart and
        which ones to claim.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-10 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">The one rule that changes everything</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          As a 1099 worker you pay <strong>two</strong> federal taxes on your profit: self-employment tax
          (15.3% for Social Security and Medicare) and regular federal income tax. The key insight is that they are
          calculated from different starting points, so a deduction can lower one, the other, or both.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          <strong>Business expenses on Schedule C reduce your net profit</strong> — the number both taxes are built on.
          That makes them the most valuable deductions you have: a legitimate business expense lowers your
          self-employment tax <em>and</em> your income tax at the same time. Other deductions are taken after net profit
          is already set, so they only shave your income tax. Understanding that split tells you where each dollar of
          savings actually lands.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-indigo-100 bg-indigo-50/60 p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900">The two buckets, in one line</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm">
            <strong>Schedule C expenses</strong> lower net profit → cut <em>both</em> SE tax and income tax.
            <strong>Above-the-line and special deductions</strong> (half of SE tax, health insurance, retirement, QBI)
            → cut income tax <em>only</em>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Deductions that lower BOTH taxes (Schedule C expenses)</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          These are ordinary, necessary costs of running your business. Each one comes straight off your gross income to
          arrive at net profit, so each one works twice as hard for you. The most common categories for freelancers:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Home office</strong> — if you use part of your home regularly and exclusively for work, deduct it with the <strong>simplified method</strong> (a flat rate per square foot) or the <strong>actual-expense method</strong> (a business-use share of rent, utilities, and upkeep).</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Mileage &amp; vehicle</strong> — deduct business driving using the <strong>IRS standard mileage rate for the year</strong> (multiply business miles by the rate) or the actual-cost method. Keep a mileage log either way.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Phone &amp; internet</strong> — the business-use portion of your cell phone and home internet bills.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Supplies &amp; software</strong> — laptops, tools, subscriptions, and apps you use to do the work.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Education</strong> — courses, books, and training that maintain or improve skills for your current business.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          The list goes on — advertising, bank fees, professional services, business insurance, and travel all belong
          here too. If a cost is genuinely part of earning your 1099 income, it likely reduces net profit. When you enter
          expenses into the
          <a href="/" class="text-indigo-600 font-medium underline decoration-indigo-200 hover:decoration-indigo-500">1099 tax calculator</a>,
          you can watch both taxes drop as you add them.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Deductions that lower income tax only</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          These are still worth thousands, but they come <em>after</em> net profit is calculated — so they leave your
          self-employment tax untouched and reduce only your federal income tax:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Half of your self-employment tax</strong> — the IRS lets you deduct 50% of the SE tax you owe as an above-the-line deduction. It happens automatically on your return; no receipts needed.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Self-employed health insurance</strong> — premiums you pay for yourself, a spouse, and dependents are an above-the-line deduction, subject to limits (generally capped at your business profit).</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Retirement contributions</strong> — a <strong>SEP-IRA</strong> or <strong>Solo 401(k)</strong> lets you set aside a large share of profit for retirement and deduct it from income. It reduces income tax, not SE tax.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>20% QBI deduction</strong> — the Qualified Business Income deduction can remove up to <strong>20% of your qualified business profit</strong> from taxable income. It is one of the largest breaks available to the self-employed, but it phases out at higher incomes and depends on your business type.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Because these don't reduce net profit, they can't shrink your 15.3% self-employment tax — but stacking them
          can still remove a substantial slice of what you'd otherwise pay in income tax.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Why the difference matters in real numbers</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Suppose you have $60,000 of net profit and you're deciding between two moves. Add a $2,000
          <strong>Schedule C expense</strong> (say, a new laptop and software) and it lowers net profit — so it saves you
          roughly 15.3% in SE tax <em>plus</em> your income-tax rate on that $2,000. Put that same $2,000 into a
          <strong>SEP-IRA</strong> and you only save your income-tax rate; the SE tax on it is already locked in.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-gradient-to-br from-slate-50 to-white p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900">The takeaway</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm">
            Don't skip retirement or health-insurance deductions — they're valuable. But <strong>track every business
            expense first</strong>, because Schedule C deductions are the only ones that dent your self-employment tax.
            Many freelancers overpay simply by forgetting small, recurring costs that add up over a year.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">How to make sure you claim them all</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">A few habits keep deductions organized and defensible:</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Use a separate business bank account</strong> so business and personal spending never mix.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Keep every receipt and a mileage log</strong> — digital photos are fine as long as they're saved.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Record expenses as they happen</strong>, not in a panic every April.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Only deduct the business portion</strong> of mixed-use costs like your phone, internet, or car.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Once you know your expected profit after deductions, plug the numbers into the
          <a href="/" class="text-indigo-600 font-medium underline decoration-indigo-200 hover:decoration-indigo-500">1099 tax calculator</a>
          to see your estimated self-employment and income tax — and how much every deduction is really saving you.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <section id="faq">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-3">
          {faqs.map((f) => (
            <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white px-5 open:shadow-sm transition">
              <summary class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer list-none font-semibold text-slate-800 py-4">
                {f.q}
                <span class="ml-4 shrink-0 grid place-items-center w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-slate-100 text-slate-500 group-open:bg-indigo-100 group-open:text-indigo-700 group-open:rotate-45 transition">+</span>
              </summary>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed pb-5 -mt-1">{f.a}</p>
            </details>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="rounded-2xl bg-indigo-50 border border-indigo-100 p-6 text-center">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">See what your deductions save you</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Enter your 1099 income and expenses to estimate your self-employment and income tax in seconds.</p>
        <a href="/" class="mt-4 inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-xl bg-indigo-600 text-white font-semibold px-5 py-3 hover:bg-indigo-700 transition">Open the 1099 tax calculator →</a>
      </div>

      <!-- Related guides -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900">Related guides</h2>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2">
          <li><a href="/guides/qbi-deduction" class="text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800 underline decoration-indigo-200 hover:decoration-indigo-500">The 20% QBI deduction explained</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/self-employment-tax-explained" class="text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800 underline decoration-indigo-200 hover:decoration-indigo-500">Self-employment tax explained</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/quarterly-estimated-taxes" class="text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-800 underline decoration-indigo-200 hover:decoration-indigo-500">How to pay quarterly estimated taxes</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 leading-relaxed border-t border-slate-100 pt-6">
        Disclaimer: This guide is for educational purposes only and does not constitute tax, legal, or financial advice.
        Tax rules change and individual situations vary. Verify details with the IRS or a qualified tax professional
        before making decisions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
